### Previous canonical companion history snapshot (before v3.0.0)

````markdown
# planning-verify-issue-premise-before-implementing — History

## v2.3.0 (2026-06-20)

**Changed by:** ProjectHermes issue #674 planning (consolidated follow-up from #428 — claimed a helper `wait_for_messages()` was "already implemented and tested" and the fix was "mechanical")
**Verification:** verified-local — the git/grep checks (`grep -rn wait_for_messages tests/`, `git merge-base --is-ancestor 0f6da0c HEAD`, `git branch -a --contains 0f6da0c`) were run this session and produced the cited results; the resulting test plan itself was NOT yet executed in CI.

### What changed

- **MINOR bump (2.2.0 → 2.3.0): adds the GREP-THE-WORKING-TREE-FIRST instance and a CITED-SITE RE-CLASSIFICATION step.** v2.0.0–v2.2.0 covered: artifact-on-unmerged-branch (scan all branches, make PR self-contained) and prerequisite-not-merged-for-auto-generated-follow-up (merge-gate). v2.3.0 adds the cleanest, smallest case of the same family: a follow-up issue that flatly asserts prior work "already exists / is mechanical" when a single `grep -rn <symbol> <dir>` against the working tree returns nothing.
- **PRIMARY new lesson (When to Use bullet + Verified-Workflow step + Failed Attempts row):** before labeling a fix "mechanical," grep the WORKING TREE for the named artifact (function/file/symbol). No match ⇒ the premise is false on this branch even if the symbol exists somewhere in history. ProjectHermes #674 claimed `wait_for_messages()` was "already implemented and tested"; `grep -rn wait_for_messages tests/` returned NO matches. The helper was authored in commit `0f6da0c` on the UNMERGED `428-auto-impl` branch (`git merge-base --is-ancestor 0f6da0c HEAD` → not an ancestor; `git branch -a --contains 0f6da0c` → only `428-auto-impl`). Consequence: the plan scope EXPANDED — it must ADD the helper to `tests/helpers.py` AND apply it, not merely apply an existing helper.
- **SECONDARY new lesson (Failed Attempts row + Results block):** re-open and re-classify EVERY cited line number / test against the real precondition; locate by SYMBOL, not by line. #674 cited 8 test line numbers and claimed all share the race, but one cited site (`test_loop_resets_backoff_when_connection_healthy`) had NO `received` list — its `sleep(0.1)` is a loop-tick timing wait, not a delivery wait, so `wait_for_messages` does not apply. Classifying by "does a `received` list exist and is asserted after the sleep?" caught the miscategorization.
- Extended the description + tags only minimally (the existing description already covers the unmerged-branch/auto-generated-follow-up surface). Added the ProjectHermes #674 worked example to Results & Parameters and a Verified On row.

### Why

Same search surface as the existing skill — "planning a follow-up issue whose premise names prior-work artifacts that may live on an unmerged branch." #674 is the canonical minimal instance: one grep falsifies the premise. It belongs in this family rather than a new skill; someone searching "the issue says the helper already exists / the fix is mechanical" should land here alongside the #556 (artifact-on-unmerged-branch) and #182 (prerequisite-not-merged) cases.

### Previous version (v2.2.0) snapshot

The full v2.2.0 text is preserved in git history at the commit preceding this amendment (branch `skill/planning-verify-unmerged-helper-branch-claims`). v2.2.0 covered: repo-wide existence scan; self-contained-vs-blocked-on-merge; vendor-fixes-latent-bugs; script-specific CI runtime deps; deterministic-gate-vs-human-ratification; and prerequisite MERGE-STATE verification for auto-generated follow-up issues. v2.3.0 leaves all of that intact and adds the grep-the-working-tree-first instance plus the cited-site re-classification discipline.

---

## v2.2.0 (2026-06-20)

**Changed by:** ProjectProteus issue #182 planning (follow-up auto-generated "from implementation of #5"; prerequisite PR #173 still OPEN)
**Verification:** unverified (plan unexecuted) — but the dependency-state CHECKS (`gh pr view 173`, `git show origin/5-auto-impl:justfile`, `grep test-all justfile` on main) were run and observed locally (verified-local for the checks)

### What changed

- **MINOR bump (2.1.0 → 2.2.0): adds the MIRROR-IMAGE failure to the v2.0.0/v2.1.0 lineage — verifying a prerequisite's actual MERGE STATE for an auto-generated follow-up issue.** v2.0.0/v2.1.0 covered the case where the artifact EXISTS on an unmerged branch (scan all branches, make the PR self-contained). v2.2.0 covers the case where a follow-up issue ASSUMES the prerequisite already merged when it did NOT, and the new work (a hook referencing a recipe) cannot be made self-contained — so a hard merge-gate is the correct disposition.
- **PRIMARY new lesson (Detailed Step 0 + Quick Reference step 0 + Failed Attempts row):** when an issue is "follow-up from #X" / auto-generated by #X's implementation, do NOT trust that #X's artifacts are on `main`. Verify MERGE STATE: `gh pr view <PR> --json state,mergedAt,headRefName` must be MERGED (not just OPEN/exists); `gh issue view <issue> --json state` OPEN is a red flag; prove the artifact is on the branch the new work RUNS on (`git show origin/<branch>:<file>` vs `grep` on main). If unmerged and the work can't be self-contained, encode an explicit merge-gate (`Depends on #X`, a step that HALTS).
- **SECONDARY new lesson (Failed Attempts row):** flag any claim the issue sources from an external doc you cannot open ("plan lines 526-540") as an UNVERIFIED-source assumption, not fact.
- Added the ProjectProteus #182 worked example to Results & Parameters (merge-state check block incl. the `git show … | diff -` byte-identical scoping check) and a Verified On row.
- Rewrote Overview (Date 2026-06-20, Objective, Outcome, Verification, History), added two When-to-Use bullets (auto-generated-from-#X; hook/edit referencing a prerequisite artifact), and extended the description + tags (`merge-state`, `prerequisite-verification`, `auto-generated-issue`, `depends-on`, `merge-gate`, `unverified-source`).

### Why

This is the same search surface as the existing skill — "planning a follow-up issue / prerequisite-dependency verification" — so it amends here rather than spawning `verify-prerequisite-merge-state-before-followup-planning`. The existing skill's lineage already runs from "verify the premise / artifact existence" through "scan all branches" to "merge-ordering disposition"; the merge-state check for auto-generated follow-ups is the natural next member of that family. Someone searching for "did the prerequisite PR actually merge before I build on it" would land here.

### Previous version (v2.1.0) snapshot

The full v2.1.0 text is preserved in git history at the commit preceding this amendment (branch `skill/verify-prerequisite-merge-state`). v2.1.0's body covered: repo-wide existence scan; self-contained-vs-blocked-on-merge; vendor-fixes-latent-bugs; script-specific CI runtime deps; deterministic-gate-vs-human-ratification. v2.2.0 leaves all of that intact and adds the merge-state-for-auto-generated-follow-up layer on top.

